ton, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Leighton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Leighton or Layton. Most, as for example those in Bedfordshire, Cambridgeshire, Cheshire, Lancashire, and Shropshire, are named with Old English <i>lēac</i> ‘leek’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’, but Layton in Durham derives from Old English <i>ge-lād</i> ‘road’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The English pronunciation of <i>Leighton</i> is usually /lɛ:tən/ or /leitən/ (also spelled   Layton   and   Leaton  ), but it can also be heard as /laitən/ or as /li:tən/ (also spelled   Leaton  ), and occasionally as /lɛtən/ (spelled   Letton  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Layton","meanings":["English: variant of   Leighton  ."]},{"name":"Slayton","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Leighton   (compare   Layton  ) with the addition of initial <i>S-</i>. Alternatively, perhaps a variant of   Sladen   or of <b>Sleightholme</b>, principally a habitational name from Sleightholme Dale in Kirkbymoorside, but perhaps occasionally from Sleightholme in Bowes or the lost Sleightholme in Lythe. The placenames derive from Old Norse <i>sléttr</i> ‘smooth, level’ + <i>holmr</i> ‘small island, water meadow’. This surname is now very rare in Britain. Compare   Slaydon  ."]},{"name":"Leaton","meanings":["English: variant of   Leighton  ."]},{"name":"Laughton","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Laughton en le Morthen in Yorkshire, Laughton in Leicestershire or any of the two places called Laughton in Lincolnshire (one near Gainsborough and another near Folkingham). The places are named with Old English <i>lēac</i> ‘leek’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure’, meaning ‘village or farm where leeks are grown’. It may sometimes have alternated with   Leighton  , which is mostly from placenames with the same etymology.","variant of   Lawton  ."]},{"name":"Letton","meanings":["English: habitational name, most probably from Letton in Norfolk or Latton in Essex. It could also be a variant of   Leighton   or   Laughton  . Most of the places so named have the same etymology as Letton and Latton, i.e. ‘farm where leeks are grown’ (Old English <i>lēac-tūn</i>). Another possibility is that it is a variant of   Latten  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":8,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":17,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Leighton was born in 1320, in Leighton, Shropshire, England, his father, Richard Leighton, was 47 and his mother, Johanna Pigott, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Matilda Cambray. He died in 1350, in Shropshire, England, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1320–1350":"1320–1350","1325–Male":"1325–Surnud","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1350–1454":"1350–1454","1274–Male":"1274–Surnud","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1300":"1300","1454":"1454","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","1274":"1274","1350":"1350","1319":"1319","1328":"1328","Leighton Shropshire, England":"Leig